[2026-03-15T16:18:24Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017imd37FNDhLNWcKEzP2m4D","type":"tool_result","content":"<persisted-output>\nOutput too large (67KB). Full output saved to: /home/agent/.claude/projects/-workspace/41846d44-0d79-434c-81b9-81f7289ac468/tool-results/toolu_017imd37FNDhLNWcKEzP2m4D.txt\n\nPreview (first 2KB):\n     1→# Self-Evolution System Implementation Plan\n     2→\n     3→> **For Claude:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use superpowers:executing-plans to implement this plan task-by-task.\n     4→\n     5→**Goal:** Implement a daemon-side post-run evolution pipeline that analyzes workflow history to automatically improve prompts, add validation steps, and refine workflows.\n     6→\n     7→**Architecture:** Multi-stage LLM pipeline (Collector → Classifier → Reflector → Executor branches) running in the daemon after each workflow completion. Three executor branches: Prompt Curator (ACE-style), Script Generator (LLM code gen), DSL Mutator (deterministic Go). Changes auto-applied with JSONL audit trail and snapshots.\n     8→\n     9→**Tech Stack:** Go, SQLite, gRPC, TOML config (`github.com/BurntSushi/toml`), existing LLM agent invocation pattern.\n    10→\n    11→**Design doc:** `docs/plans/2026-02-24-self-evolution-design.md`\n    12→\n    13→---\n    14→\n    15→## Task 1: Extend Domain Types\n    16→\n    17→**Files:**\n    18→- Modify: `internal/domain/run.go`\n    19→- Modify: `internal/domain/workflow.go`\n    20→- Test: `internal/domain/run_test.go`\n    21→\n    22→**Step 1: Write failing test for Run.ProjectDir**\n    23→\n    24→Add to `internal/domain/run_test.go`:\n    25→\n    26→```go\n    27→func TestRunProjectDir(t *testing.T) {\n    28→\tr := NewRun(\"test-1\", \"develop\")\n    29→\tr.ProjectDir = \"/home/user/project\"\n    30→\tassert.Equal(t, \"/home/user/project\", r.ProjectDir)\n    31→}\n    32→```\n    33→\n    34→**Step 2: Run test to verify it fails**\n    35→\n    36→Run: `go test ./internal/domain/ -run TestRunProjectDir -v`\n    37→Expected: FAIL — `r.ProjectDir undefined`\n    38→\n    39→**Step 3: Add ProjectDir to Run**\n    40→\n    41→In `internal/domain/run.go`, add `ProjectDir string` to the `Run` struct.\n    42→\n    43→**Step 4: Run test to verify it passes**\n    44→\n    45→Run: `go test ./internal/domain/ -run TestRunProjectDir -v`\n    46→Expected: PASS\n    47→\n...\n</persisted-output>"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01YNtMJ1cKQdPtGDZdFVC9hG","session_id":"41846d44-0d79-434c-81b9-81f7289ac468","uuid":"7eb142d4-a7b4-4f6d-99ee-eb13672fbf22"}
[2026-03-15T16:18:24Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01YWXZT9pPwsJy4crc6HXK9E","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Safety Guide\n     2→\n     3→This document covers good practices for using Cloche securely. The central concern is\n     4→the **Lethal Trifecta** of LLM-powered agent usage: when a system simultaneously has\n     5→(1) access to private data, (2) exposure to untrusted content, and (3) the ability to\n     6→communicate externally, it becomes vulnerable to prompt injection attacks that can\n     7→exfiltrate sensitive information. Cloche's architecture is designed to let you break this\n     8→trifecta, but only if you configure it correctly.\n     9→\n    10→## The Lethal Trifecta\n    11→\n    12→Any system that combines all three of the following is at risk:\n    13→\n    14→1. **Access to private data** — The agent can read source code, credentials, API keys,\n    15→   internal documentation, or customer data.\n    16→2. **Exposure to untrusted content** — The agent processes inputs that an attacker could\n    17→   influence: issue descriptions, pull request comments, dependency READMEs, web pages,\n    18→   or fetched API responses.\n    19→3. **Ability to communicate externally** — The agent can make HTTP requests, send emails,\n    20→   push to remote repositories, or otherwise transmit data outside the local environment.\n    21→\n    22→When all three are present, a prompt injection hidden in untrusted content can instruct\n    23→the agent to exfiltrate private data through the external communication channel. The\n    24→defense is to remove at least one leg of the trifecta.\n    25→\n    26→Cloche helps by isolating agent work inside containers where you control filesystem\n    27→access and network egress. But the host side of Cloche has no such isolation — host-side\n    28→agent steps run with the daemon's full OS privileges. The recommendations below focus on\n    29→keeping host-side exposure minimal and container-side access locked down.\n    30→\n    31→## Minimize Host-Side Agent Usage\n    32→\n    33→Host workflows (those with a `host { }` block) run directly on the host machine. Agent\n    34→steps in host workflows inherit the daemon's permissions: full filesystem, full network,\n    35→all environment variables.\n    36→\n    37→**Prefer container workflows for agent work.** The `workflow` step type in host workflows\n    38→dispatches work to an isolated container. Use it:\n    39→\n    40→```\n    41→workflow \"main\" {\n    42→  step prepare-prompt {\n    43→    run = \".cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    44→    results = [success, fail]\n    45→  }\n    46→\n    47→  step develop {\n    48→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    49→    results = [success, fail]\n    50→  }\n    51→\n    52→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n    53→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n    54→  develop:success        -> done\n    55→  develop:fail           -> abort\n    56→}\n    57→```\n    58→\n    59→In this pattern, the host workflow uses a *script* step (deterministic, no LLM) to\n    60→prepare the prompt and a *workflow* step to dispatch it to a container. No agent step\n    61→runs on the host.\n    62→\n    63→**If you must use host-side agent steps**, limit what the agent can access:\n    64→\n    65→- Run the daemon under a dedicated service account with restricted filesystem\n    66→  permissions rather than your personal user account.\n    67→- Avoid setting broad environment variables (cloud credentials, database URLs) in the\n    68→  daemon's environment. Only export what is strictly needed.\n    69→- Keep host workflows simple — use them for orchestration (scripts and workflow dispatch),\n    70→  not for direct agent work.\n    71→\n    72→## Network Allowlisting\n    73→\n    74→Containers should have the minimum network access needed for their task. The workflow DSL\n    75→accepts a `network_allow` list in the `container {}` block to declare intended egress\n    76→restrictions:\n    77→\n    78→```\n    79→workflow \"develop\" {\n    80→  container {\n    81→    image         = \"my-project:latest\"\n    82→    network_allow = [\"api.anthropic.com\", \"github.com\"]\n    83→  }\n    84→\n    85→  step implement {\n    86→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    87→    results = [success, fail]\n    88→  }\n    89→\n    90→  implement:success -> done\n    91→  implement:fail    -> abort\n    92→}\n    93→```\n    94→\n    95→> **Note:** `network_allow` is currently parsed by the DSL but not enforced at runtime —\n    96→> containers run with unrestricted network access. Until enforcement is implemented, use\n    97→> the Docker-level controls described below to actually restrict egress. Declaring\n    98→> `network_allow` in your workflow is still recommended as documentation of intent and to\n    99→> be ready when enforcement lands.\n   100→\n   101→A good allowlist includes only:\n   102→\n   103→- The AI provider API endpoint (e.g. `api.anthropic.com`)\n   104→- Your git remote for pushing results (e.g. `github.com`)\n   105→- Language-specific package registries only if the workflow installs dependencies\n   106→\n   107→Everything else — documentation sites, third-party APIs, general internet — should be\n   108→excluded unless the task specifically requires it. The agent may be less capable without\n   109→web access, but the security tradeoff is worth it for tasks involving sensitive code.\n   110→\n   111→### Docker Network Isolation\n   112→\n   113→Since `network_allow` is not yet enforced, Docker-level network restrictions are\n   114→currently the primary mechanism for limiting container egress. Configure them in your\n   115→project's Dockerfile or via Docker runtime options:\n   116→\n   117→**Drop all network by default.** If your workflow does not need any network (e.g. pure\n   118→code editing with tests), override the container's network at the Docker level:\n   119→\n   120→```dockerfile\n   121→# In your .cloche/Dockerfile — no network-dependent steps\n   122→FROM cloche-base:latest\n   123→# Install all dependencies at build time so no runtime downloads needed\n   124→COPY requirements.txt .\n   125→RUN pip install -r requirements.txt\n   126→```\n   127→\n   128→When all dependencies are baked into the image, the container needs no outbound access\n   129→except for the AI provider API.\n   130→\n   131→**Restrict DNS resolution.** Containers use Docker's embedded DNS by default. For\n   132→tighter control, you can specify DNS servers that only resolve your allowlisted domains,\n   133→or use a DNS-based firewall.\n   134→\n   135→**Avoid `--privileged` and `--cap-add`.** Cloche containers do not need elevated\n   136→capabilities. The base image runs as an unprivileged `agent` user. Never run Cloche\n   137→containers with `--privileged` or add capabilities like `NET_ADMIN` unless you have a\n   138→specific, justified need.\n   139→\n   140→## Filesystem Isolation\n   141→\n   142→Cloche containers get a *copy* of your project, not a bind mount. This is a deliberate\n   143→security choice:\n   144→\n   145→- The agent cannot modify your host filesystem directly.\n   146→- Changes are only extracted back via `docker cp` to a git branch after the run\n   147→  completes.\n   148→- You review the changes in a branch before merging.\n   149→\n   150→**Keep this model intact.** Avoid using `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` to bind-mount sensitive\n   151→host directories into containers. If you need additional files in the container, prefer\n   152→the `.cloche/overrides/` mechanism, which copies files at container start time.\n   153→\n   154→**Audit override files.** Everything in `.cloche/overrides/` is applied on top of\n   155→`/workspace/` in the container. Do not place credentials or sensitive configuration in\n   156→this directory — it is checked into version control.\n   157→\n   158→## Credential Handling\n   159→\n   160→**API keys.** The `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` environment variable is automatically passed into\n   161→containers. Other environment variables must be explicitly passed via `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV`.\n   162→Only pass what the agent needs.\n   163→\n   164→**Git credentials.** Cloche copies `~/.claude` and `~/.claude.json` into containers for\n   165→agent authentication. These are copied (not mounted) so concurrent runs do not conflict.\n   166→Be aware that these files are present in the container filesystem during the run.\n   167→\n   168→**Do not bake secrets into Docker images.** Use environment variables or runtime\n   169→injection rather than embedding API keys, tokens, or passwords in your Dockerfile or\n   170→`.cloche/overrides/`.\n   171→\n   172→```\n   173→# Good: pass at runtime\n   174→CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV=DATABASE_URL=postgres://... cloche run develop\n   175→\n   176→# Bad: in Dockerfile\n   177→ENV DATABASE_URL=postgres://...\n   178→```\n   179→\n   180→## Prompt Hygiene\n   181→\n   182→The content of prompts is the primary vector for injection attacks. Untrusted content\n   183→that reaches an agent's prompt can instruct it to take unintended actions.\n   184→\n   185→**Separate trusted and untrusted content.** Prompt templates in `.cloche/prompts/` are\n   186→trusted — you write and review them. User requests (task descriptions, issue bodies) are\n   187→untrusted — they come from external sources. Cloche's prompt assembly concatenates these,\n   188→so the agent sees both. Keep the trusted template's instructions clear and explicit to\n   189→reduce the chance of injection overriding them.\n   190→\n   191→**Validate external inputs in script steps.** Use host-side script steps to sanitize or\n   192→filter task descriptions before passing them to agent steps. For example,\n   193→`.cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh` can strip HTML, limit length, or reject suspicious\n   194→patterns before writing to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\n   195→\n   196→**Limit feedback content.** The `feedback = \"true\"` step config includes previous output\n   197→logs in the prompt. If those logs contain content from untrusted sources (e.g. test\n   198→output that includes user-supplied data), this is another injection surface. Only enable\n   199→feedback when needed.\n   200→\n   201→## Review Before Merge\n   202→\n   203→Cloche extracts results to git branches, not directly to your main branch. Always review\n   204→the agent's changes before merging:\n   205→\n   206→- Check for unexpected file modifications outside the task scope.\n   207→- Look for new dependencies, network calls, or credential usage that the task did not\n   208→  require.\n   209→- Verify that no files were added that could serve as persistence mechanisms (cron jobs,\n   210→  git hooks, CI config changes).\n   211→\n   212→This review step is your final safeguard. Automated agents are powerful but not\n   213→infallible — treat their output with the same scrutiny you would give any external\n   214→contribution.\n   215→\n   216→## Summary\n   217→\n   218→| Risk | Mitigation |\n   219→|------|-----------|\n   220→| Host-side agent has full access | Use container workflows for agent steps; keep host workflows to scripts and dispatch |\n   221→| Unrestricted network in container | Declare `network_allow`; enforce with Docker-level network controls until runtime enforcement lands |\n   222→| Sensitive files in container | Rely on copy-based isolation; avoid bind mounts; audit overrides |\n   223→| Credentials leaking | Pass via env vars at runtime, not in images or overrides |\n   224→| Prompt injection | Sanitize untrusted inputs in script steps; keep prompt templates explicit |\n   225→| Malicious agent output | Review branches before merging; check for unexpected changes |\n   226→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01YNtMJ1cKQdPtGDZdFVC9hG","session_id":"41846d44-0d79-434c-81b9-81f7289ac468","uuid":"d1bfa5cf-c739-44ca-aa33-5ee0480eca88"}
