[2026-03-15T16:18:24Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_013hB6MiSPC8DHwnHf1uUVU6","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Gemini Browser — Design Document\n     2→\n     3→## Overview\n     4→\n     5→A synchronous, CLI-based Gemini protocol browser written in Rust. It connects to\n     6→Gemini servers over TLS (port 1965), renders `text/gemini` content with ANSI\n     7→colors, and provides an interactive REPL for navigating links, history, and\n     8→arbitrary URLs. Long pages are displayed with pagination so that content does not\n     9→scroll off-screen.\n    10→\n    11→---\n    12→\n    13→## Module Structure\n    14→\n    15→```\n    16→src/\n    17→├── main.rs        — Entry point, REPL loop, command dispatch\n    18→├── gemini.rs      — TLS connection, request/response, status handling\n    19→├── parser.rs      — text/gemini line-type parser\n    20→├── render.rs      — ANSI terminal renderer for parsed lines\n    21→├── pager.rs       — Paginated display of rendered output\n    22→└── url_utils.rs   — URL parsing, normalization, relative resolution\n    23→```\n    24→\n    25→### Dependency graph\n    26→\n    27→```\n    28→main\n    29→ ├── gemini      (fetch pages)\n    30→ ├── parser      (parse body into lines)\n    31→ ├── render      (format parsed lines into styled strings)\n    32→ ├── pager       (paginate and display rendered output)\n    33→ └── url_utils   (resolve URLs)\n    34→\n    35→gemini\n    36→ └── url_utils   (normalize request URL, resolve redirects)\n    37→```\n    38→\n    39→`parser`, `render`, `pager`, and `url_utils` have no internal cross-dependencies.\n    40→`pager` operates on plain `Vec<String>` (the formatted output lines from\n    41→`render`) and has no knowledge of Gemini types.\n    42→\n    43→---\n    44→\n    45→## Data Types\n    46→\n    47→### `url_utils.rs`\n    48→\n    49→```rust\n    50→/// Parse a gemini:// URL string into a `url::Url`.\n    51→/// Ensures scheme is \"gemini\", default port 1965, default path \"/\".\n    52→pub fn parse_gemini_url(raw: &str) -> Result<Url, GeminiError>\n    53→\n    54→/// Resolve a potentially-relative URL against a base URL.\n    55→/// Handles absolute gemini:// URLs, protocol-relative, and relative paths.\n    56→pub fn resolve_url(base: &Url, reference: &str) -> Result<Url, GeminiError>\n    57→```\n    58→\n    59→No custom structs — uses `url::Url` directly.\n    60→\n    61→### `gemini.rs`\n    62→\n    63→```rust\n    64→/// A parsed Gemini response.\n    65→pub struct GeminiResponse {\n    66→    pub status: u8,           // two-digit status code (10–69)\n    67→    pub meta: String,         // the META field (MIME type, redirect URL, message, etc.)\n    68→    pub body: Option<Vec<u8>>, // body bytes; present only for 2x SUCCESS responses\n    69→}\n    70→\n    71→/// Fetch a Gemini page. Handles the full request/response cycle for a single URL.\n    72→/// Does NOT follow redirects — the caller handles redirect logic.\n    73→pub fn fetch(url: &Url) -> Result<GeminiResponse, GeminiError>\n    74→\n    75→/// Navigate to a URL, following redirects. Returns the final response and the final URL.\n    76→pub fn fetch_with_redirects(start_url: &Url) -> Result<(GeminiResponse, Url), GeminiError>\n    77→\n    78→/// Check for redirect loops and max hops.\n    79→pub fn check_redirect(visited: &[String], target: &str, max_hops: usize) -> Result<(), GeminiError>\n    80→```\n    81→\n    82→Internally, `fetch` performs:\n    83→1. DNS resolution and TCP connect (with 5-second timeout).\n    84→2. TLS handshake via `rustls` with certificate verification disabled.\n    85→3. Sends `<URL>\\r\\n`.\n    86→4. Reads and parses the response header line.\n    87→5. For 2x status, reads the body (up to 5 MB).\n    88→6. Returns `GeminiResponse`.\n    89→\n    90→### `parser.rs`\n    91→\n    92→```rust\n    93→/// A single parsed line of text/gemini content.\n    94→#[derive(Debug, PartialEq)]\n    95→pub enum GeminiLine {\n    96→    Text(String),\n    97→    Link { url: String, label: String },\n    98→    Heading { level: u8, text: String },      // level 1, 2, or 3\n    99→    ListItem(String),\n   100→    Quote(String),\n   101→    PreformattedToggle { alt_text: String },   // ``` with optional alt text\n   102→    PreformattedText(String),                  // a line inside a preformatted block\n   103→}\n   104→\n   105→/// Parse a text/gemini document body into a Vec<GeminiLine>.\n   106→/// Tracks preformatted toggle state: lines between ``` markers become\n   107→/// PreformattedText; the ``` lines themselves become PreformattedToggle.\n   108→pub fn parse_gemini(body: &str) -> Vec<GeminiLine>\n   109→```\n   110→\n   111→### `render.rs`\n   112→\n   113→```rust\n   114→/// Render parsed gemini lines into ANSI-formatted strings.\n   115→/// Returns a tuple of (output_lines, link_urls):\n   116→/// - output_lines: Vec<String> of formatted lines ready for display (one per output line)\n   117→/// - link_urls: Vec<String> of link URLs found on the page (indexed from 1)\n   118→///\n   119→/// Does NOT print to stdout — the caller (via the pager) handles display.\n   120→pub fn render(lines: &[GeminiLine]) -> (Vec<String>, Vec<String>)\n   121→```\n   122→\n   123→ANSI codes used:\n   124→- **Heading 1**: bold + bright cyan (`\\x1b[1;96m`)\n   125→- **Heading 2**: bold (`\\x1b[1m`)\n   126→- **Heading 3**: bold (`\\x1b[1m`)\n   127→- **Links**: cyan (`\\x1b[36m`), prefixed with `[N] ` where N is the 1-based link index\n   128→- **Quotes**: dim italic (`\\x1b[2;3m`)\n   129→- **Preformatted text**: printed as-is, no special styling, no line wrapping\n   130→- **List items**: printed with a `  • ` bullet prefix\n   131→- All styled lines end with a reset (`\\x1b[0m`)\n   132→\n   133→Each formatted line is a complete `String` (no trailing newline). The render\n   134→function builds these strings using `format!()` instead of `println!()`.\n   135→\n   136→### `pager.rs`\n   137→\n   138→```rust\n   139→/// Paginated display for rendered output lines.\n   140→///\n   141→/// When a page's content exceeds the terminal height, the Pager shows one\n   142→/// screenful at a time, allowing the user to scroll forward and backward\n   143→/// through the content using `next`/`prev` commands at the REPL prompt.\n   144→pub struct Pager {\n   145→    lines: Vec<String>,       // all rendered output lines\n   146→    offset: usize,            // index of the first line on the current page\n   147→    page_height: usize,       // number of content lines per page (terminal height - 1)\n   148→}\n   149→\n   150→impl Pager {\n   151→    /// Create a new Pager for the given lines.\n   152→    /// `page_height` is the number of content lines per page (typically\n   153→    /// terminal_height - 1, reserving one line for the status/pager prompt).\n   154→    pub fn new(lines: Vec<String>, page_height: usize) -> Self\n   155→\n   156→    /// Print the current page of lines to stdout.\n   157→    /// After the content lines, if there is more content beyond the current\n   158→    /// page, prints a status line: `[Page X/Y — 'n':next 'p':prev]`\n   159→    pub fn display_current_page(&self)\n   160→\n   161→    /// Advance to the next page. Returns true if the page changed,\n   162→    /// false if already at the last page.\n   163→    pub fn next_page(&mut self) -> bool\n   164→\n   165→    /// Go back to the previous page. Returns true if the page changed,\n   166→    /// false if already at the first page.\n   167→    pub fn prev_page(&mut self) -> bool\n   168→\n   169→    /// Returns true if the content requires pagination (more lines than page_height).\n   170→    pub fn needs_pagination(&self) -> bool\n   171→\n   172→    /// Returns the total number of pages.\n   173→    pub fn total_pages(&self) -> usize\n   174→\n   175→    /// Returns the current page number (1-indexed).\n   176→    pub fn current_page(&self) -> usize\n   177→}\n   178→\n   179→/// Detect the terminal height in rows.\n   180→///\n   181→/// Strategy:\n   182→/// 1. Try the LINES environment variable (set by many terminals/shells).\n   183→/// 2. Try reading from the terminal via libc ioctl TIOCGWINSZ on stdout.\n   184→/// 3. Fall back to a default of 24 rows.\n   185→pub fn terminal_height() -> usize\n   186→```\n   187→\n   188→### `main.rs` — Navigation State\n   189→\n   190→```rust\n   191→/// Holds the browser's runtime state.\n   192→struct BrowserState {\n   193→    history: Vec<Url>,        // stack of previously visited URLs (for `back`)\n   194→    current_url: Option<Url>, // the URL of the currently displayed page\n   195→    links: Vec<String>,       // link URLs extracted from the current page (1-indexed)\n   196→    pager: Option<Pager>,     // active pager for the current page (None if no page loaded\n   197→                              // or content fits on one screen)\n   198→}\n   199→```\n   200→\n   201→Commands parsed from the REPL prompt:\n   202→\n   203→```rust\n   204→enum Command {\n   205→    FollowLink(usize),   // a number like \"3\"\n   206→    Back,                 // \"back\" or \"b\"\n   207→    Go(String),           // \"go <url>\"\n   208→    Quit,                 // \"quit\" or \"q\"\n   209→    Help,                 // \"help\" or \"?\"\n   210→    Navigate(String),     // bare \"gemini://...\" URL\n   211→    NextPage,             // \"next\" or \"n\"\n   212→    PrevPage,             // \"prev\" or \"p\"\n   213→    Empty,\n   214→    Unknown,\n   215→}\n   216→```\n   217→\n   218→### Error types (defined in `gemini.rs`, used everywhere)\n   219→\n   220→```rust\n   221→use thiserror::Error;\n   222→\n   223→#[derive(Error, Debug)]\n   224→pub enum GeminiError {\n   225→    #[error(\"invalid URL: {0}\")]\n   226→    InvalidUrl(String),\n   227→\n   228→    #[error(\"connection failed: {0}\")]\n   229→    ConnectionFailed(String),\n   230→\n   231→    #[error(\"TLS error: {0}\")]\n   232→    TlsError(String),\n   233→\n   234→    #[error(\"timeout connecting to server\")]\n   235→    Timeout,\n   236→\n   237→    #[error(\"invalid response header: {0}\")]\n   238→    InvalidResponse(String),\n   239→\n   240→    #[error(\"response body too large (exceeds 5 MB)\")]\n   241→    BodyTooLarge,\n   242→\n   243→    #[error(\"too many redirects\")]\n   244→    TooManyRedirects,\n   245→\n   246→    #[error(\"redirect loop detected\")]\n   247→    RedirectLoop,\n   248→\n   249→    #[error(\"IO error: {0}\")]\n   250→    Io(#[from] std::io::Error),\n   251→}\n   252→```\n   253→\n   254→---\n   255→\n   256→## Protocol Flow\n   257→\n   258→When the user navigates to a URL (via `go <url>`, link number, or bare URL):\n   259→\n   260→### 1. URL parsing / resolution\n   261→\n   262→- If triggered by a link number, look up the raw URL string from `links[n-1]`.\n   263→  Resolve it against `current_url` using `url_utils::resolve_url`.\n   264→- If triggered by `go <url>` or a bare gemini:// URL, parse it with\n   265→  `url_utils::parse_gemini_url`.\n   266→- Validation: scheme must be `gemini`, host must be present. Default port 1965,\n   267→  default path `/`.\n   268→\n   269→### 2. Redirect-following loop\n   270→\n   271→Wrap steps 3–5 in a loop that follows 3x redirects:\n   272→- Maintain a `Vec<String>` of visited URLs (as strings) for loop detection.\n   273→- Limit to **5 hops**. If exceeded, return `GeminiError::TooManyRedirects`.\n   274→- Before each hop, check if the redirect target is already in the visited set.\n   275→  If so, return `GeminiError::RedirectLoop`.\n   276→\n   277→### 3. TLS connection\n   278→\n   279→- Open a `std::net::TcpStream` to `host:port` with a **5-second** connect\n   280→  timeout (`TcpStream::connect_timeout`).\n   281→- Set read/write timeouts to 5 seconds on the stream.\n   282→- Build a `rustls::ClientConfig` with a custom `ServerCertVerifier` that accepts\n   283→  all certificates (returns `Ok(ServerCertVerified::assertion())` for every\n   284→  call). Use `webpki-roots` as the root store (required by the API even though\n   285→  we skip verification).\n   286→- Wrap the stream in `rustls::StreamOwned<rustls::ClientConnection, TcpStream>`.\n   287→\n   288→### 4. Request sending\n   289→\n   290→- Write `{url}\\r\\n` (the full URL including scheme) to the TLS stream.\n   291→\n   292→### 5. Response header parsing\n   293→\n   294→- Read bytes from the TLS stream until `\\r\\n` is found (or until 1024 + 2 bytes\n   295→  to guard against overlong headers — META is capped at 1024 bytes by spec).\n   296→- Split the header line at the first space. The first part is the two-digit\n   297→  status code; the remainder is META.\n   298→- Validate: status must be two ASCII digits in range 10–69. If not, return\n   299→  `GeminiError::InvalidResponse`.\n   300→\n   301→### 6. Body reading (for 2x responses only)\n   302→\n   303→- Read the rest of the stream into a `Vec<u8>`.\n   304→- Enforce a **5 MB** limit: if total bytes exceed 5,242,880, stop reading and\n   305→  return `GeminiError::BodyTooLarge`.\n   306→- For non-2x statuses, `body` is `None`.\n   307→\n   308→### 7. Status dispatch (back in `main.rs`)\n   309→\n   310→Based on the first digit of the status code:\n   311→\n   312→| Status | Action |\n   313→|--------|--------|\n   314→| **1x INPUT** | Print the META string as a prompt. Read a line from stdin. URL-encode it and append as `?query` to the original URL. Re-fetch. |\n   315→| **2x SUCCESS** | If META starts with `text/gemini` (or is empty, defaulting to `text/gemini`), parse and render the body. For any other MIME type, print `[Received <META>, not rendering]`. |\n   316→| **3x REDIRECT** | META is the redirect URL. Resolve against current URL. Continue the redirect loop (step 2). |\n   317→| **4x TEMP FAILURE** | Print `Temporary failure ({status}): {meta}`. Return to prompt. |\n   318→| **5x PERM FAILURE** | Print `Permanent failure ({status}): {meta}`. Return to prompt. |\n   319→| **6x CLIENT CERT** | Print `Client certificates are not supported.` Return to prompt. |\n   320→\n   321→### 8. Rendering and pagination\n   322→\n   323→On a successful 2x response with `text/gemini` content:\n   324→\n   325→1. Parse the body with `parser::parse_gemini()`.\n   326→2. Render the parsed lines with `render::render()`, which returns\n   327→   `(output_lines, link_urls)` — a vector of ANSI-formatted strings and a\n   328→   vector of link URLs.\n   329→3. Determine the terminal height via `pager::terminal_height()`.\n   330→4. If the number of output lines exceeds `terminal_height - 1`:\n   331→   - Create a `Pager` with `page_height = terminal_height - 1`.\n   332→   - Call `pager.display_current_page()` to show the first screenful.\n   333→   - Store the `Pager` in `state.pager`.\n   334→5. If the content fits on one screen:\n   335→   - Print all output lines directly to stdout (one `println!` per line).\n   336→   - Set `state.pager` to `None`.\n   337→6. Store the link URLs in `state.links`.\n   338→\n   339→### 9. State update and prompt\n   340→\n   341→- On successful page display (2x with renderable content):\n   342→  - Push the old `current_url` (if any) onto `history`.\n   343→  - Set `current_url` to the new URL.\n   344→  - Store the `links` vector returned by `render`.\n   345→  - Store or clear the `pager` as described in step 8.\n   346→- Print `> ` and read the next command.\n   347→\n   348→---\n   349→\n   350→## Pagination Behavior\n   351→\n   352→### Display\n   353→\n   354→When the Pager is active (content exceeds one screen), `display_current_page()`\n   355→prints lines from `offset` to `offset + page_height`, followed by a status line:\n   356→\n   357→```\n   358→[Page 1/5 — 'n':next 'p':prev]\n   359→```\n   360→\n   361→This status line uses dim ANSI styling (`\\x1b[2m`) so it's visually distinct\n   362→from page content. It is only shown when the content requires pagination.\n   363→\n   364→When content fits on a single screen, all lines are printed directly with no\n   365→status line, and `state.pager` is `None`.\n   366→\n   367→### Commands\n   368→\n   369→Two new REPL commands control pagination:\n   370→\n   371→- `next` or `n`: advance to the next page. If already on the last page, print\n   372→  `\"Already on the last page.\"`. If no pager is active, print\n   373→  `\"No page to scroll.\"`.\n   374→- `prev` or `p`: go back to the previous page. If already on the first page,\n   375→  print `\"Already on the first page.\"`. If no pager is active, print\n   376→  `\"No page to scroll.\"`.\n   377→\n   378→All existing commands remain available while paginated content is displayed.\n   379→The user can follow links, go back, navigate to a new URL, etc. at any time.\n   380→When the user navigates away (via link, `go`, `back`, etc.), the current pager\n   381→is replaced or cleared.\n   382→\n   383→### Page calculation\n   384→\n   385→- `page_height = terminal_height - 1` (reserve 1 line for the status/prompt).\n   386→- `total_pages = ceil(total_lines / page_height)`.\n   387→- `current_page = (offset / page_height) + 1`.\n   388→- `next_page()`: sets `offset = min(offset + page_height, last_page_offset)`.\n   389→- `prev_page()`: sets `offset = offset.saturating_sub(page_height)`.\n   390→\n   391→### Terminal height detection\n   392→\n   393→`pager::terminal_height()` determines the terminal height:\n   394→\n   395→1. Check the `LINES` environment variable. If set and parses as a positive\n   396→   integer, use it.\n   397→2. On Unix, use `libc::ioctl` with `TIOCGWINSZ` on `STDOUT_FILENO` to query\n   398→   the terminal dimensions. If successful, use the `ws_row` field.\n   399→3. Fall back to a default of **24 rows**.\n   400→\n   401→This requires adding `libc` as a dependency in `Cargo.toml`.\n   402→\n   403→---\n   404→\n   405→## REPL Command Parsing\n   406→\n   407→Read a line from stdin. Trim whitespace. Match:\n   408→\n   409→1. Empty line → do nothing, re-prompt.\n   410→2. `\"quit\"` or `\"q\"` → exit process.\n   411→3. `\"back\"` or `\"b\"` → pop from `history`. If empty, print\n   412→   `\"No previous page.\"`. Otherwise navigate to the popped URL.\n   413→4. `\"help\"` or `\"?\"` → print help text (including pagination commands).\n   414→5. `\"next\"` or `\"n\"` → show next page of current content.\n   415→6. `\"prev\"` or `\"p\"` → show previous page of current content.\n   416→7. `\"go \"` prefix → strip prefix, treat remainder as a URL, navigate.\n   417→8. Starts with `\"gemini://\"` → treat entire input as a URL, navigate.\n   418→9. Parses as `usize` → follow that link number. If out of range, print\n   419→   `\"Invalid link number.\"`.\n   420→10. Anything else → print `\"Unknown command. Type 'help' for available commands.\"`.\n   421→\n   422→The updated help text:\n   423→\n   424→```\n   425→Commands:\n   426→  <number>       Follow link by number\n   427→  back, b        Go to previous page\n   428→  go <url>       Navigate to a URL\n   429→  gemini://...   Navigate to a Gemini URL\n   430→  next, n        Next page (when content is paginated)\n   431→  prev, p        Previous page (when content is paginated)\n   432→  help, ?        Show this help\n   433→  quit, q        Exit the browser\n   434→```\n   435→\n   436→### Command priority\n   437→\n   438→`\"n\"` is matched as the `NextPage` command **before** attempting to parse it as a\n   439→number. This means a user cannot type `\"n\"` to follow a link — but since link\n   440→numbers are always displayed numerically (`[1]`, `[2]`, etc.), this is not a\n   441→conflict. Similarly, `\"p\"` is matched as `PrevPage` before number parsing.\n   442→The match order in `parse_command` must handle this: check for string commands\n   443→(`quit`, `back`, `help`, `next`, `prev`, `go`) before attempting `usize` parse.\n   444→\n   445→---\n   446→\n   447→## Edge Cases\n   448→\n   449→### Connection / network errors\n   450→- `TcpStream::connect_timeout` returns `Err` on timeout or connection refused →\n   451→  display `\"Error: connection failed: {details}\"`, return to prompt.\n   452→- TLS handshake failure → display `\"Error: TLS error: {details}\"`, return to\n   453→  prompt.\n   454→\n   455→### Malformed response headers\n   456→- No `\\r\\n` found within 1026 bytes → `InvalidResponse(\"header line too long\")`.\n   457→- Status code not two digits → `InvalidResponse(\"invalid status code\")`.\n   458→- Status code outside 10–69 → `InvalidResponse(\"status code out of range\")`.\n   459→- Missing META after status for 1x/3x (where META is required) →\n   460→  `InvalidResponse(\"missing meta\")`.\n   461→\n   462→### Redirect chains\n   463→- Track each URL visited during the redirect chain in a `Vec<String>`.\n   464→- After 5 hops without a non-3x response → `TooManyRedirects`.\n   465→- If a redirect target matches any previously visited URL in the chain →\n   466→  `RedirectLoop`.\n   467→\n   468→### Response body size\n   469→- Read body in a loop, accumulating into a `Vec<u8>`.\n   470→- After each read, check `total_len > 5_242_880`. If exceeded, return\n   471→  `BodyTooLarge`.\n   472→\n   473→### Preformatted toggle state\n   474→- `parser::parse_gemini` maintains a `bool` flag `in_preformatted`.\n   475→- A line starting with ` ``` ` toggles the flag and emits a `PreformattedToggle`.\n   476→- While `in_preformatted` is true, **all** lines are emitted as\n   477→  `PreformattedText` regardless of their content — no link/heading/etc. parsing.\n   478→- The flag starts `false` at the beginning of each document.\n   479→- If the document ends while `in_preformatted` is still true, that is valid — the\n   480→  preformatted block is implicitly closed.\n   481→\n   482→### Empty body / missing META\n   483→- A 2x response with empty META → default MIME type is `text/gemini`.\n   484→- A 2x response with an empty body → display nothing, still update state and\n   485→  show prompt. Pager is set to `None` (nothing to paginate).\n   486→\n   487→### Input status (1x)\n   488→- URL-encode the user's input before appending as query string. Use\n   489→  percent-encoding for non-ASCII and reserved characters.\n   490→- If the user provides empty input, still re-request with an empty `?` query.\n   491→\n   492→### Back on empty history\n   493→- Print `\"No previous page.\"` and stay at the current page.\n   494→\n   495→### Link number out of range\n   496→- Print `\"Invalid link number.\"` if < 1 or > number of links on the page.\n   497→- Also print this if a number is entered when no page has been loaded yet\n   498→  (`links` is empty).\n   499→\n   500→### Pagination edge cases\n   501→\n   502→- **Content fits on one screen**: No pager is created. `state.pager` is `None`.\n   503→  `next`/`prev` commands print `\"No page to scroll.\"`.\n   504→- **Exactly one page of content**: `page_height` lines or fewer. No pager is\n   505→  created (same as above).\n   506→- **Empty page**: No output lines. No pager. `next`/`prev` print\n   507→  `\"No page to scroll.\"`.\n   508→- **Terminal height detection failure**: Falls back to 24 rows, so\n   509→  `page_height = 23`.\n   510→- **Very small terminal** (e.g., 1–3 rows): `page_height` could be 0 or very\n   511→  small. If `page_height < 1`, clamp it to 1 to avoid division by zero or\n   512→  empty pages.\n   513→- **Last page has fewer lines than page_height**: `display_current_page()`\n   514→  prints only the remaining lines (from `offset` to the end of `lines`).\n   515→- **Non-text/gemini content**: No rendering/pagination happens. The\n   516→  `[Received <MIME>, not rendering]` message is printed directly. Pager is\n   517→  cleared.\n   518→- **Navigation clears pager**: When navigating to a new page (via link, `go`,\n   519→  `back`, or bare URL), the previous pager state is discarded and replaced with\n   520→  the new page's pager (or `None` if the new content fits on screen).\n   521→\n   522→---\n   523→\n   524→## Module Public APIs (Summary)\n   525→\n   526→### `url_utils.rs`\n   527→```\n   528→pub fn parse_gemini_url(raw: &str) -> Result<Url, GeminiError>\n   529→pub fn resolve_url(base: &Url, reference: &str) -> Result<Url, GeminiError>\n   530→```\n   531→\n   532→### `gemini.rs`\n   533→```\n   534→pub struct GeminiResponse { pub status: u8, pub meta: String, pub body: Option<Vec<u8>> }\n   535→pub enum GeminiError { InvalidUrl, ConnectionFailed, TlsError, Timeout, InvalidResponse, BodyTooLarge, TooManyRedirects, RedirectLoop, Io }\n   536→pub fn fetch(url: &Url) -> Result<GeminiResponse, GeminiError>\n   537→pub fn fetch_with_redirects(start_url: &Url) -> Result<(GeminiResponse, Url), GeminiError>\n   538→pub fn check_redirect(visited: &[String], target: &str, max_hops: usize) -> Result<(), GeminiError>\n   539→pub fn parse_response_header(line: &str) -> Result<(u8, String), GeminiError>\n   540→```\n   541→\n   542→### `parser.rs`\n   543→```\n   544→pub enum GeminiLine { Text, Link, Heading, ListItem, Quote, PreformattedToggle, PreformattedText }\n   545→pub fn parse_gemini(body: &str) -> Vec<GeminiLine>\n   546→```\n   547→\n   548→### `render.rs`\n   549→```\n   550→pub fn render(lines: &[GeminiLine]) -> (Vec<String>, Vec<String>)\n   551→                                        // (output_lines, link_urls)\n   552→```\n   553→\n   554→### `pager.rs`\n   555→```\n   556→pub struct Pager { lines: Vec<String>, offset: usize, page_height: usize }\n   557→  pub fn new(lines: Vec<String>, page_height: usize) -> Self\n   558→  pub fn display_current_page(&self)\n   559→  pub fn next_page(&mut self) -> bool\n   560→  pub fn prev_page(&mut self) -> bool\n   561→  pub fn needs_pagination(&self) -> bool\n   562→  pub fn total_pages(&self) -> usize\n   563→  pub fn current_page(&self) -> usize\n   564→pub fn terminal_height() -> usize\n   565→```\n   566→\n   567→### `main.rs` (not public — internal to the binary)\n   568→```\n   569→struct BrowserState { history, current_url, links, pager }\n   570→enum Command { FollowLink, Back, Go, Quit, Help, Navigate, NextPage, PrevPage, Empty, Unknown }\n   571→fn parse_command(input: &str) -> Command\n   572→fn navigate(state: &mut BrowserState, url: Url)\n   573→fn handle_response(state: &mut BrowserState, response: GeminiResponse, url: Url)\n   574→fn print_help()\n   575→fn main()\n   576→```\n   577→\n   578→---\n   579→\n   580→## Dependencies\n   581→\n   582→`Cargo.toml`:\n   583→```toml\n   584→[dependencies]\n   585→rustls = { version = \"0.23\", features = [\"ring\"] }\n   586→webpki-roots = \"0.26\"\n   587→url = \"2\"\n   588→thiserror = \"2\"\n   589→libc = \"0.2\"        # terminal size detection via ioctl\n   590→```\n   591→\n   592→The `libc` crate is added solely for `pager::terminal_height()` to call\n   593→`ioctl(STDOUT_FILENO, TIOCGWINSZ, ...)` for reliable terminal size detection.\n   594→\n   595→---\n   596→\n   597→## Test Strategy\n   598→\n   599→All tests use `#[cfg(test)] mod tests` blocks within their respective modules.\n   600→No tests require network access.\n   601→\n   602→### `url_utils.rs` tests\n   603→\n   604→| Test | What it covers |\n   605→|------|---------------|\n   606→| `test_parse_basic_url` | Parses `gemini://example.com/path` correctly |\n   607→| `test_parse_default_port` | Absent port defaults to 1965 |\n   608→| `test_parse_default_path` | `gemini://example.com` gets path `/` |\n   609→| `test_parse_with_explicit_port` | `gemini://example.com:1966/` preserves port |\n   610→| `test_reject_non_gemini_scheme` | `https://example.com` returns `InvalidUrl` |\n   611→| `test_reject_missing_host` | `gemini:///path` returns `InvalidUrl` |\n   612→| `test_resolve_absolute_url` | Resolving `gemini://other.com/page` against any base returns the absolute URL |\n   613→| `test_resolve_relative_path` | Resolving `page2` against `gemini://host/dir/page1` gives `gemini://host/dir/page2` |\n   614→| `test_resolve_relative_root` | Resolving `/other` against `gemini://host/dir/page` gives `gemini://host/other` |\n   615→| `test_resolve_parent_path` | Resolving `../up` against `gemini://host/a/b/c` gives `gemini://host/a/up` |\n   616→\n   617→### `gemini.rs` tests\n   618→\n   619→Since `fetch` requires a network, tests focus on response header parsing. Extract header parsing into an internal helper `parse_response_header(line: &str) -> Result<(u8, String), GeminiError>` and test it.\n   620→\n   621→| Test | What it covers |\n   622→|------|---------------|\n   623→| `test_parse_success_header` | `\"20 text/gemini\"` → status 20, meta `\"text/gemini\"` |\n   624→| `test_parse_input_header` | `\"10 Enter your name\"` → status 10, meta `\"Enter your name\"` |\n   625→| `test_parse_redirect_header` | `\"31 gemini://other/path\"` → status 31 |\n   626→| `test_parse_temp_failure` | `\"40 Server busy\"` → status 40 |\n   627→| `test_parse_perm_failure` | `\"51 Not found\"` → status 51 |\n   628→| `test_parse_cert_required` | `\"60 Certificate required\"` → status 60 |\n   629→| `test_parse_empty_meta` | `\"20 \"` → status 20, meta is empty string (or just whitespace trimmed) |\n   630→| `test_parse_meta_no_space` | `\"20\"` with no space → status 20, meta is empty |\n   631→| `test_reject_single_digit` | `\"2 text\"` → `InvalidResponse` |\n   632→| `test_reject_non_numeric` | `\"AB text\"` → `InvalidResponse` |\n   633→| `test_reject_status_out_of_range` | `\"70 whatever\"` → `InvalidResponse` |\n   634→| `test_reject_status_too_low` | `\"09 whatever\"` → `InvalidResponse` |\n   635→| `test_redirect_loop_detection` | Unit test for the redirect-visited-set logic: visiting the same URL twice triggers `RedirectLoop` |\n   636→| `test_redirect_max_hops` | After 5 hops, `TooManyRedirects` is returned |\n   637→| `test_redirect_ok` | A valid redirect hop succeeds |\n   638→\n   639→### `parser.rs` tests\n   640→\n   641→| Test | What it covers |\n   642→|------|---------------|\n   643→| `test_text_line` | Plain text becomes `Text(\"...\")` |\n   644→| `test_link_with_label` | `\"=> gemini://x/y Link text\"` → `Link { url, label }` |\n   645→| `test_link_without_label` | `\"=> gemini://x/y\"` → `Link` with label equal to url |\n   646→| `test_link_extra_whitespace` | `\"=>   gemini://x   some label\"` handles extra spaces |\n   647→| `test_heading_h1` | `\"# Title\"` → `Heading { level: 1, text: \"Title\" }` |\n   648→| `test_heading_h2` | `\"## Subtitle\"` → level 2 |\n   649→| `test_heading_h3` | `\"### Sub-sub\"` → level 3 |\n   650→| `test_list_item` | `\"* Item\"` → `ListItem(\"Item\")` |\n   651→| `test_quote_line` | `\"> Quoted\"` → `Quote(\"Quoted\")` |\n   652→| `test_preformatted_block` | Three lines (toggle, content, toggle) produce `PreformattedToggle`, `PreformattedText`, `PreformattedToggle` |\n   653→| `test_preformatted_no_parsing` | A link-like line inside preformatted block becomes `PreformattedText`, NOT `Link` |\n   654→| `test_preformatted_alt_text` | `` ```alt `` → `PreformattedToggle { alt_text: \"alt\" }` |\n   655→| `test_preformatted_unclosed` | Document ends while preformatted → no error, lines are `PreformattedText` |\n   656→| `test_empty_document` | Empty string → empty Vec |\n   657→| `test_mixed_content` | Full document with all line types produces correct sequence |\n   658→\n   659→### `render.rs` tests\n   660→\n   661→Render tests verify the returned data (link URLs and formatted output lines).\n   662→Exact ANSI output is validated where useful but tests primarily focus on the\n   663→returned link list and the structural correctness of output lines.\n   664→\n   665→| Test | What it covers |\n   666→|------|---------------|\n   667→| `test_render_returns_links` | Rendering a page with 3 links returns link_urls of length 3 with correct URLs |\n   668→| `test_render_link_numbering` | Links are numbered starting from 1 (checked via output_lines content) |\n   669→| `test_render_empty_page` | Empty input returns empty link_urls and empty output_lines |\n   670→| `test_render_output_line_count` | Number of output_lines matches number of non-toggle input lines |\n   671→| `test_render_heading_format` | Heading output lines contain the heading text and ANSI bold codes |\n   672→| `test_render_preformatted_toggle_hidden` | PreformattedToggle lines produce no output lines (toggle markers are not displayed) |\n   673→\n   674→### `pager.rs` tests\n   675→\n   676→| Test | What it covers |\n   677→|------|---------------|\n   678→| `test_needs_pagination_short` | Content shorter than page_height → `needs_pagination()` returns false |\n   679→| `test_needs_pagination_long` | Content longer than page_height → `needs_pagination()` returns true |\n   680→| `test_needs_pagination_exact` | Content exactly equal to page_height → `needs_pagination()` returns false |\n   681→| `test_total_pages` | 25 lines with page_height 10 → total_pages is 3 |\n   682→| `test_total_pages_exact` | 20 lines with page_height 10 → total_pages is 2 |\n   683→| `test_total_pages_single` | 5 lines with page_height 10 → total_pages is 1 |\n   684→| `test_total_pages_empty` | 0 lines → total_pages is 1 (or 0; design choice — use 1 to avoid displaying \"page 0/0\") |\n   685→| `test_current_page_initial` | Newly created Pager → current_page is 1 |\n   686→| `test_next_page_advances` | After `next_page()`, current_page increases by 1 |\n   687→| `test_next_page_at_end` | `next_page()` at last page returns false, current_page unchanged |\n   688→| `test_prev_page_at_start` | `prev_page()` at first page returns false, current_page unchanged |\n   689→| `test_prev_page_goes_back` | After advancing then calling `prev_page()`, current_page decreases |\n   690→| `test_page_height_clamp` | page_height of 0 is clamped to 1 |\n   691→\n   692→### `main.rs` tests\n   693→\n   694→| Test | What it covers |\n   695→|------|---------------|\n   696→| `test_parse_quit` | `\"quit\"` and `\"q\"` parse as `Command::Quit` |\n   697→| `test_parse_back` | `\"back\"` and `\"b\"` parse as `Command::Back` |\n   698→| `test_parse_help` | `\"help\"` and `\"?\"` parse as `Command::Help` |\n   699→| `test_parse_go` | `\"go gemini://example.com\"` parses as `Command::Go` |\n   700→| `test_parse_navigate` | `\"gemini://example.com/path\"` parses as `Command::Navigate` |\n   701→| `test_parse_follow_link` | `\"3\"` parses as `Command::FollowLink(3)` |\n   702→| `test_parse_empty` | `\"\"` and `\"  \"` parse as `Command::Empty` |\n   703→| `test_parse_unknown` | `\"foo\"` parses as `Command::Unknown` |\n   704→| `test_parse_next` | `\"next\"` and `\"n\"` parse as `Command::NextPage` |\n   705→| `test_parse_prev` | `\"prev\"` and `\"p\"` parse as `Command::PrevPage` |\n   706→\n   707→---\n   708→\n   709→## Implementation Notes\n   710→\n   711→### TLS setup with certificate skipping\n   712→\n   713→Create a struct implementing `rustls::client::danger::ServerCertVerifier` that\n   714→returns `Ok(ServerCertVerified::assertion())` from `verify_server_cert` and\n   715→`Ok(HandshakeSignatureValid::assertion())` from `verify_tls12_signature` and\n   716→`verify_tls13_signature`. Provide a `supported_verify_schemes` method returning\n   717→`rustls::crypto::ring::default_provider().signature_verification_algorithms.supported_schemes()`.\n   718→\n   719→Build `ClientConfig` via:\n   720→```\n   721→ClientConfig::builder()\n   722→    .dangerous()\n   723→    .with_custom_certificate_verifier(Arc::new(NoVerifier))\n   724→    .with_no_client_auth()\n   725→```\n   726→\n   727→Install the default crypto provider at program start with\n   728→`rustls::crypto::ring::default_provider().install_default()`.\n   729→\n   730→### Body reading with size limit\n   731→\n   732→```rust\n   733→let mut body = Vec::new();\n   734→let mut total = 0usize;\n   735→let mut buf = [0u8; 8192];\n   736→loop {\n   737→    match stream.read(&mut buf) {\n   738→        Ok(0) => break,\n   739→        Ok(n) => {\n   740→            total += n;\n   741→            if total > 5_242_880 { return Err(GeminiError::BodyTooLarge); }\n   742→            body.extend_from_slice(&buf[..n]);\n   743→        }\n   744→        Err(e) if e.kind() == io::ErrorKind::ConnectionAborted => break,\n   745→        Err(e) => return Err(GeminiError::Io(e)),\n   746→    }\n   747→}\n   748→```\n   749→\n   750→### URL query encoding for input (1x)\n   751→\n   752→Use `url::form_urlencoded::Serializer` or manual percent-encoding. Set the\n   753→query portion of the URL via `url.set_query(Some(&encoded_input))`.\n   754→\n   755→### Header reading\n   756→\n   757→Read byte-by-byte (or small buffer) scanning for `\\r\\n`. Accumulate into a\n   758→buffer of max 1026 bytes. This avoids over-reading into the body.\n   759→\n   760→### render.rs migration to non-printing\n   761→\n   762→The `render()` function must change from printing directly to stdout (via\n   763→`println!()`) to building a `Vec<String>` of formatted lines. Each existing\n   764→`println!(\"{CYAN}[{index}] {label}{RESET}\")` becomes a\n   765→`format!(\"{CYAN}[{index}] {label}{RESET}\")` pushed onto the output vector.\n   766→`PreformattedToggle` lines toggle internal state but do **not** produce an\n   767→output line. The return type changes from `Vec<String>` (just links) to\n   768→`(Vec<String>, Vec<String>)` (output_lines, link_urls). Existing tests that\n   769→destructure the return value as a single `Vec<String>` must be updated to use\n   770→the tuple.\n   771→\n   772→### Pager display logic\n   773→\n   774→```rust\n   775→pub fn display_current_page(&self) {\n   776→    let end = std::cmp::min(self.offset + self.page_height, self.lines.len());\n   777→    for line in &self.lines[self.offset..end] {\n   778→        println!(\"{line}\");\n   779→    }\n   780→    if self.needs_pagination() {\n   781→        println!(\n   782→            \"\\x1b[2m[Page {}/{} — 'n':next 'p':prev]\\x1b[0m\",\n   783→            self.current_page(),\n   784→            self.total_pages()\n   785→        );\n   786→    }\n   787→}\n   788→```\n   789→\n   790→### Terminal height via ioctl\n   791→\n   792→```rust\n   793→pub fn terminal_height() -> usize {\n   794→    // 1. Check LINES env var\n   795→    if let Ok(val) = std::env::var(\"LINES\") {\n   796→        if let Ok(n) = val.parse::<usize>() {\n   797→            if n > 0 {\n   798→                return n;\n   799→            }\n   800→        }\n   801→    }\n   802→\n   803→    // 2. ioctl TIOCGWINSZ\n   804→    #[cfg(unix)]\n   805→    {\n   806→        use libc::{ioctl, winsize, STDOUT_FILENO, TIOCGWINSZ};\n   807→        let mut ws: winsize = unsafe { std::mem::zeroed() };\n   808→        if unsafe { ioctl(STDOUT_FILENO, TIOCGWINSZ, &mut ws) } == 0 && ws.ws_row > 0 {\n   809→            return ws.ws_row as usize;\n   810→        }\n   811→    }\n   812→\n   813→    // 3. Default\n   814→    24\n   815→}\n   816→```\n   817→\n   818→### Integration in main.rs\n   819→\n   820→The key change in `handle_response` for the 2x SUCCESS case:\n   821→\n   822→```rust\n   823→// Parse and render\n   824→let parsed = parser::parse_gemini(&body_str);\n   825→let (output_lines, links) = render::render(&parsed);\n   826→\n   827→// Determine pagination\n   828→let height = pager::terminal_height();\n   829→let page_height = std::cmp::max(height.saturating_sub(1), 1);\n   830→\n   831→if output_lines.len() > page_height {\n   832→    let mut pg = pager::Pager::new(output_lines, page_height);\n   833→    pg.display_current_page();\n   834→    state.pager = Some(pg);\n   835→} else {\n   836→    for line in &output_lines {\n   837→        println!(\"{line}\");\n   838→    }\n   839→    state.pager = None;\n   840→}\n   841→\n   842→// Update navigation state\n   843→if let Some(old_url) = state.current_url.take() {\n   844→    state.history.push(old_url);\n   845→}\n   846→state.current_url = Some(url);\n   847→state.links = links;\n   848→```\n   849→\n   850→And in the REPL loop, the new command handlers:\n   851→\n   852→```rust\n   853→Command::NextPage => {\n   854→    if let Some(ref mut pg) = state.pager {\n   855→        if pg.next_page() {\n   856→            pg.display_current_page();\n   857→        } else {\n   858→            println!(\"Already on the last page.\");\n   859→        }\n   860→    } else {\n   861→        println!(\"No page to scroll.\");\n   862→    }\n   863→}\n   864→Command::PrevPage => {\n   865→    if let Some(ref mut pg) = state.pager {\n   866→        if pg.prev_page() {\n   867→            pg.display_current_page();\n   868→        } else {\n   869→            println!(\"Already on the first page.\");\n   870→        }\n   871→    } else {\n   872→        println!(\"No page to scroll.\");\n   873→    }\n   874→}\n   875→```\n   876→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01YNtMJ1cKQdPtGDZdFVC9hG","session_id":"41846d44-0d79-434c-81b9-81f7289ac468","uuid":"fb0ada40-322a-452c-ba34-07ae45bcf84e"}
